\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {8}{\ignorespaces Coupling matrices with their prescribed marginals. The central grayscale image displays $P_{ij}$; the red curve on the left is the source marginal $\mathrm  {a}$, the blue curve on top is the target marginal $\mathrm  {b}$, and the thin red curve inside the matrix is the barycentric projection $i\DOTSB \mapstochar \rightarrow \DOTSB \sum@ \slimits@ _j P_{ij}j/a_i$. The independent product plan is diffuse, whereas the one-dimensional optimal plan concentrates near the monotone quantile correspondence. The dense discretization is the same construction with 200 bins.}}{15}{figure.3.8}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:kantorovich-coupling-matrix-marginals}{{8}{15}{Coupling matrices with their prescribed marginals. The central grayscale image displays $P_{ij}$; the red curve on the left is the source marginal $\a $, the blue curve on top is the target marginal $\b $, and the thin red curve inside the matrix is the barycentric projection $i\mapsto \sum _j P_{ij}j/a_i$. The independent product plan is diffuse, whereas the one-dimensional optimal plan concentrates near the monotone quantile correspondence. The dense discretization is the same construction with 200 bins}{figure.3.8}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {9}{\ignorespaces From permutation matrices to splitting couplings. When the two empirical measures have the same number of atoms and uniform weights, an optimal plan can be a permutation matrix. Once target masses are nonuniform, the admissible set $\mathrm  {U}(\mathrm  {a},\mathrm  {b})$ also contains plans in which one source sends mass to several targets and several sources merge into the same target.}}{16}{figure.3.9}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:kantorovich-permutation-versus-splitting}{{9}{16}{From permutation matrices to splitting couplings. When the two empirical measures have the same number of atoms and uniform weights, an optimal plan can be a permutation matrix. Once target masses are nonuniform, the admissible set $\CouplingsD (\a ,\b )$ also contains plans in which one source sends mass to several targets and several sources merge into the same target}{figure.3.9}{}}
