\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {25}{\ignorespaces Hard $c$-transforms for the bilinear cost $c(x,y)=-xy$. Red curves are deliberately non-concave initial potentials $f$ and $g$. Violet curves are the double-transform closures $f^{c\bar  c}$ and $g^{\bar  c c}$, which are concave majorants. Dashed blue curves are the one-sided best responses $g^{\bar  c}$ and $f^c$, displayed after a harmless vertical gauge shift. The figure illustrates why exact alternating best responses are useful for dual certificates but do not give the smooth iterative dynamics later provided by entropic regularization.}}{45}{figure.5.25}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:dual-alternating-c-transform-failure}{{25}{45}{Hard $c$-transforms for the bilinear cost $c(x,y)=-xy$. Red curves are deliberately non-concave initial potentials $f$ and $g$. Violet curves are the double-transform closures $f^{c\bar c}$ and $g^{\bar c c}$, which are concave majorants. Dashed blue curves are the one-sided best responses $g^{\bar c}$ and $f^c$, displayed after a harmless vertical gauge shift. The figure illustrates why exact alternating best responses are useful for dual certificates but do not give the smooth iterative dynamics later provided by entropic regularization}{figure.5.25}{}}
