\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {32}{\ignorespaces Debiasing by point optimization. The red level sets show a fixed two-Gaussian target density $\beta $, while the blue atoms are an optimized empirical measure $\alpha _n$. For small $\varepsilon $, the raw entropic cost and the Sinkhorn divergence both keep the two modes. For large $\varepsilon $, minimizing the raw cost collapses the atoms toward the barycenter predicted by the large-temperature bias, whereas the self-cost subtraction in\nobreakspace  {}\textup  {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont  (\ignorespaces \ref  {eq-sinkhorn-divergence}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}} keeps a bimodal cloud.}}{64}{figure.8.32}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:sinkhorn-divergence-debiasing}{{32}{64}{Debiasing by point optimization. The red level sets show a fixed two-Gaussian target density $\beta $, while the blue atoms are an optimized empirical measure $\alpha _n$. For small $\epsilon $, the raw entropic cost and the Sinkhorn divergence both keep the two modes. For large $\epsilon $, minimizing the raw cost collapses the atoms toward the barycenter predicted by the large-temperature bias, whereas the self-cost subtraction in~\eqref {eq-sinkhorn-divergence} keeps a bimodal cloud}{figure.8.32}{}}
