\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {33}{\ignorespaces Empirical fluctuation in dimension three. For each sample size $n$, two independent empirical measures $\alpha _n$ and $\alpha '_n$ are drawn from the same standard Gaussian law in $\mathbb  {R}^3$. The curves show the median of $D(\alpha _n,\alpha '_n)$, normalized by its value at the smallest displayed $n$, with interquartile bands. Exact OT follows the slower dimension-dependent scale, while MMD and the fixed-$\varepsilon $ Sinkhorn divergence behave closer to the parametric $n^{-1/2}$ guide. This is a statistical illustration, not a solver benchmark.}}{66}{figure.8.33}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:sinkhorn-bias-variance-tradeoff}{{33}{66}{Empirical fluctuation in dimension three. For each sample size $n$, two independent empirical measures $\al _n$ and $\al '_n$ are drawn from the same standard Gaussian law in $\RR ^3$. The curves show the median of $D(\al _n,\al '_n)$, normalized by its value at the smallest displayed $n$, with interquartile bands. Exact OT follows the slower dimension-dependent scale, while MMD and the fixed-$\epsilon $ Sinkhorn divergence behave closer to the parametric $n^{-1/2}$ guide. This is a statistical illustration, not a solver benchmark}{figure.8.33}{}}
