\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {37}{\ignorespaces Lifted min-sliced plan. A one-dimensional direction is selected by a small deterministic sweep, then red and blue atoms are sorted after projection and matched in that order. The middle panel lifts this one-dimensional matching back to the plane; it is a feasible coupling but not the same object as the quadratic $W_2$ matching shown on the right. This illustrates why sliced constructions are computationally light and interpretable, while losing some of the geometry of the full transport problem.}}{71}{figure.9.37}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:min-sliced-transport-plan}{{37}{71}{Lifted min-sliced plan. A one-dimensional direction is selected by a small deterministic sweep, then red and blue atoms are sorted after projection and matched in that order. The middle panel lifts this one-dimensional matching back to the plane; it is a feasible coupling but not the same object as the quadratic $W_2$ matching shown on the right. This illustrates why sliced constructions are computationally light and interpretable, while losing some of the geometry of the full transport problem}{figure.9.37}{}}
