\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {46}{\ignorespaces Two views of the continuity equation. The left panel advects particles and Gaussian density contours under a smooth affine vector field, showing the Lagrangian flow $x'(t)=v(x(t))$. The right panel shows the Eulerian flux $m_t=\rho _t v_t$ at an intermediate time, where $\alpha _t=\rho _t\,\mathrm  {d}x$: arrows are weighted by the local density, so the velocity contributes to the PDE only where mass is present.}}{86}{figure.12.46}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:dynamic-continuity-equation}{{46}{86}{Two views of the continuity equation. The left panel advects particles and Gaussian density contours under a smooth affine vector field, showing the Lagrangian flow $x'(t)=v(x(t))$. The right panel shows the Eulerian flux $m_t=\rho _t v_t$ at an intermediate time, where $\alpha _t=\rho _t\,\d x$: arrows are weighted by the local density, so the velocity contributes to the PDE only where mass is present}{figure.12.46}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {47}{\ignorespaces Benamou--Brenier geodesic between two sampled silhouettes. A discrete quadratic OT plan between the cat and two-disks point clouds induces the McCann interpolation $Z_t=(1-t)X+tY$, which is the Lagrangian realization of the least-action solution. The left panel shows kernel-density contours along this geodesic, and the right panel displays midpoint particles with their constant characteristic velocities $Y-X$.}}{86}{figure.12.47}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:dynamic-benamou-brenier-geodesic}{{47}{86}{Benamou--Brenier geodesic between two sampled silhouettes. A discrete quadratic OT plan between the cat and two-disks point clouds induces the McCann interpolation $Z_t=(1-t)X+tY$, which is the Lagrangian realization of the least-action solution. The left panel shows kernel-density contours along this geodesic, and the right panel displays midpoint particles with their constant characteristic velocities $Y-X$}{figure.12.47}{}}
