\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {49}{\ignorespaces Two entropy-driven Wasserstein gradient flows from the same compact initial density. The heat flow is generated by Shannon entropy $g(\rho )=\rho \qopname  \relax o{log}\rho $ and instantly develops Gaussian tails. The porous-medium flow uses the power entropy $g(\rho )=\rho ^m/(m-1)$ with $m=2$, hence $\partial _t\rho =\Delta (\rho ^2)$; it spreads more slowly and keeps a compact free boundary.}}{91}{figure.13.49}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:gradflow-heat-versus-porous-medium}{{49}{91}{Two entropy-driven Wasserstein gradient flows from the same compact initial density. The heat flow is generated by Shannon entropy $g(\rho )=\rho \log \rho $ and instantly develops Gaussian tails. The porous-medium flow uses the power entropy $g(\rho )=\rho ^m/(m-1)$ with $m=2$, hence $\partial _t\rho =\Delta (\rho ^2)$; it spreads more slowly and keeps a compact free boundary}{figure.13.49}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {50}{\ignorespaces Interaction-energy particle flows for three choices of $k$. A positive Gaussian kernel $k(x,y)=\qopname  \relax o{exp}(-|\!| x-y |\!|^2/(2\sigma ^2))$ produces short-range repulsion under Wasserstein descent; changing its sign produces attraction and collapse; adding a quadratic long-range attraction to the repulsive kernel yields a balanced attraction--repulsion dynamics. In all cases the particles follow the coupled ODE structure of\nobreakspace  {}\textup  {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont  (\ignorespaces \ref  {eq:wassflows-particles}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}}.}}{91}{figure.13.50}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:gradflow-interaction-particles}{{50}{91}{Interaction-energy particle flows for three choices of $k$. A positive Gaussian kernel $k(x,y)=\exp (-\norm {x-y}^2/(2\sigma ^2))$ produces short-range repulsion under Wasserstein descent; changing its sign produces attraction and collapse; adding a quadratic long-range attraction to the repulsive kernel yields a balanced attraction--repulsion dynamics. In all cases the particles follow the coupled ODE structure of~\eqref {eq:wassflows-particles}}{figure.13.50}{}}
