\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {52}{\ignorespaces Mean-field training of a homogeneous two-layer model as transport in neuron space. Blue rays represent teacher directions or active homogeneous features. Red neurons move as particles under a Wasserstein gradient flow, rotating and changing radius until their empirical support concentrates near the useful rays. The right panel shows the same effect in angular coordinates: the initial red directional distribution becomes concentrated around the blue teacher rays. This illustrates why support propagation in parameter space is central to the homogeneous mean-field analysis.}}{96}{figure.13.52}\protected@file@percent }
